{[%evp 0,63,50,-24,-16,-22,-14,-17,-46,-23,15,7,7,-35,12,-34,-12,-31,-11,-9,-9,
-9,48,7,13,8,8,33,75,51,128,128,132,130,130,112,121,88,99,14,84,96,106,124,85,
85,201,171,201,206,231,206,246,206,222,219,206,213,311,314,304,300,297,295,335,
336] In this lecture I will introduce you to the most important pawn
structures in Catalan Opening. The Catalan is very popular nowadays and the
theory is changing every day. I think that there are two main concepts: One is
to try to reach a risk-free position, where our light-squared bishop will put
pressure on Black's queenside. The other is to sacrifice a pawn via b2-b3 and
to obtain long-term compensation. GM Mihail Marin explained very well some of
the arising pawn structures in his database for Catalan Opening. I am trying
to present different examples and different structures. The most important
structure is The Open Centre. Open Centre is the structure where both "c" and
"d" pawns are exchanged. The positions are symmetrical so the piece activity
becomes really important. The rule here is that If Black failed to neutralize
or exchange the light-squared bishops then White is always better. In the
following game, you will see an example of how strong can be White's initiative
} 1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. d4 {Transposing to the
Catalan opening} dxc4 7. Qa4 (7. dxc5 {is the mainline nowadays}) 7... Bd7 {
The most logical.} ({White is better after} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. Bxc6+ Bd7
10. Rd1 Bxc6 ({or} 10... Qxd1+ 11. Qxd1 Bxc6 12. Nd2 $16) 11. Qxc6+ bxc6 12.
Rxd4 Rd8 13. Rxc4 Rd1+ 14. Kg2 $16) 8. Qxc4 cxd4 {This exchange activates
White´s pieces.} ({The modern theory considers stronger} 8... b5 9. Qd3 Rc8)
9. Nxd4 {[%cal Gg2b7]} Rc8 10. Nc3 Qa5 {A rare continuation. White is always
better in this kind of positions. White has a "free" initiative on the
queenside. Quite important is that White's king is safe while on the other
hand his "collegue" on e8 is still vulnerable.} ({Dubious is} 10... Qb6 $6 11.
Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Be3 $1 Qb4 (12... Qxb2 $2 13. Rab1 Qa3 14. Nb5 Qa6 15. Rfc1 $18)
13. Qxb4 Bxb4 14. Bxa7 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rxc3 17. Rfb1 {1-0 (22)
Ribli,Z (2595)-Prandstetter,E (2385)/Warsaw 1979/MCD (43)}) ({but also} 10...
Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qh4 {leaves Black with some problems.}) 11. Bd2 ({
Another possibility was} 11. Rd1 Be7 $140 12. Nb3 Qc7 13. Nb5 Qb8 14. Nc5 a6
15. Nxd7 Nxd7 {0-1 Kortschnoj,V (2670)-Karpov,A (2700)/Moscow 1974/Candidates 
(42)} 16. Nd4 $36) 11... Qc5 $6 {Quite common mistake. Black thought that he
will be safe in the endgame, but it is not true} (11... Be7 $5 12. Nb3 $14) 12.
Qxc5 Bxc5 13. Nb3 Bd6 $2 {An unfortunate move, the bishop is vulnerable on d6
and White gains an extra tempo} (13... Be7) 14. Rfd1 Ke7 $2 (14... Nd8 $6 {
can be answered by} 15. Be3 Bb8 16. Bc5 $5 (16. Nc5 Bc6) 16... Bc6 17. Rac1 $18
) (14... Be7 $142 15. Rac1 $16) 15. Nb5 $1 Bb8 16. Nc5 $1 {[%csl Rb7] Black
underestimated the strength of this manoeuvre. Now almost all White's pieces
are attacking Black's queenside.} a6 ({After} 16... b6 $2 {White wins} 17. Na6
Be5 $140 $2 18. f4 $1 Bxb2 19. Rab1 $18) 17. Na3 {White regroups the knight to
c4.} Rc7 18. Nc4 Ba7 19. b4 $5 {By protecting his knight, White gets ready for
Bf4.} (19. Nxd7 {is also strong} Nxd7 20. Rac1 $18) 19... Nd5 $2 {This moves
loses on a spot} ({Of course Black could not play} 19... Nxb4 $2 20. Nxd7 Rxc4
{because of} 21. Ne5 Rd4 22. Bxb7 {[%cal Gd2b4]} ({or} 22. e3)) (19... Nd4 $5
20. Kf1 $16) ({perhaps the best was} 19... e5 20. Bxc6 Bxc6 21. Nxe5 Bd5 22.
Be3 $16) 20. a3 $2 ({Missing the possibility to punish Black for his mistake by
} 20. Bxd5 $1 {White's light-squared bishop is usually his strongest piece and
that's why quite ofter White is even not considering such an exchange.} exd5
21. Bf4 Rcc8 22. Nd6 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5]}) 20... f6 $2 {This leads to the hopeless
position.} (20... Bxc5 $6 21. bxc5 Nd4 22. Bxd5 (22. Ba5 $2 Nxe2+ 23. Kf1 Rxc5
24. Bxd5 Rxd5 25. Kxe2 Bb5) (22. Bg5+ f6) 22... exd5 23. Nb6 $16) ({was
necessary instead} 20... Nd4 $1 21. Bxd5 (21. Bg5+ f6 22. Rxd4 Bxc5 23. bxc5
fxg5 24. Bxd5 exd5 25. Rxd5 Be6 26. Nb6 Bxd5 27. Nxd5+ Kd7 28. Nxc7 Kxc7 $11)
21... exd5 22. Ne3 Be6 23. Nxd5+ Bxd5 24. Bg5+ f6 25. Rxd4 Bc6 $14 {Black has
good compensation for the missing pawn}) 21. Bxd5 $1 {Now White doesn't miss
his chance to exchange his active bishop to win the material.} exd5 22. Bf4
Rcc8 23. Nd6 Bxc5 24. Nxc8+ Bxc8 25. bxc5 $18 {The rest is easy and doesn´t
require any comments.} Ke6 26. Rab1 g5 27. Bd6 b5 28. Rb3 Na5 29. Re3+ Kf7 30.
Re7+ Kg6 31. Rxd5 Bb7 32. Rd1 1-0

