{[%evp 0,135,-2,1,12,8,10,-15,5,-6,8,-1,4,4,0,4,15,4,15,11,15,0,3,-6,5,13,22,2,
54,-46,14,19,15,4,1,14,14,35,39,10,45,35,61,39,48,48,65,73,59,63,40,38,64,46,
41,31,31,43,59,72,72,78,79,3,10,-50,-16,48,35,51,35,40,61,61,68,61,76,64,74,64,
74,54,56,51,53,49,49,49,91,58,98,75,96,104,130,126,113,138,154,142,137,137,137,
124,125,129,133,105,133,133,136,122,63,79,173,131,136,137,136,136,137,101,101,
101,159,101,148,101,1154,982,1055,1252,1252,1262,1282,1302,1302,1312]} {[#]} 
21. Qc2 a5 {Very important structure. Black exchanged his light-squared bishop
and put his pawns on "c6" and "e6". The important nuance is that White's pawn
is on a4 and Black has an outpost on b4. We have opposite-coloured bishops
which are prerequisites for an attack. So the most natural plan in this
position is to play h4-h5. This way the king on g8 will feel always
uncomfortable, because Black can't play g7-g6 and White has the idea to create
the battery Qe4 and Bd3 or c2. The other important idea for White is to
maneuver the knight to d3 or b3.} 22. h4 $1 Nf6 23. h5 Rc7 {The problem for
Black is that there is no counterplay. Both e6-e5 and c6-c5 are not very good,
because then White's bishop will be quite active.} 24. Ne2 Qb6 25. Nf4 Nd5 26.
Rbc1 Bd6 27. Nd3 Nb4 28. Qb3 Rcd7 29. Be4 Qc7 30. Rh1 Nxd3 31. Bxd3 Be7 32. Bb1
Qd6 33. Qc2 {White succeeds with his plan and then the Black king is in danger.
Fortunately for Black he has the defense 33...Bf6 and Qh7 will be only one
check.} Bf6 34. Qc5 {Very interesting strategical decision by A. Grischuk - he
enters an endgame. White has the plan b2-b4 and also Black's king is still in
danger, even in the endgame.} Qxc5 35. Rxc5 Rd5 36. Rc4 e5 {It is
understandable that Black wants to play active because otherwise,
f2-f4-g3-g4-g5 is coming, after some preparation.} 37. Be4 R5d7 38. dxe5 Bxe5
39. b4 axb4 40. Rxb4 Ra8 41. Rhb1 Ra7 42. Bf5 Re7 43. Bc8 c5 44. Rb5 (44. Rc4
$1 Rc7 45. Bg4 $18) 44... Rc7 45. Bxb7 Rxa4 46. Bd5 Kf8 {You can see that even
in this position White's pawn on h5 is very useful. Black can't play g7-g6 and
Kg7.} 47. f4 Bc3 48. e4 (48. Rb7 $1) 48... Bd4 (48... Rb4 $1 $14) 49. e5 c4 50.
Rb8+ Ke7 51. R1b7 Ra7 52. Bc6 f5 53. Rxc7+ Rxc7 54. Ba4 Ra7 55. Rb4 Rc7 56. Kf3
$6 (56. Bc2 Ke6 57. Ra4 $18 {[%cal Ra4a6]}) 56... Ke6 57. Bc2 Ba7 58. Ra4 Bb6
59. Ke2 (59. Ra6 $1 Rb7 60. Ke2 {[%cal Re2d2,Rd2c3]}) 59... Kd5 60. Bxf5 Ra7
61. Rxa7 Bxa7 {Dominguez defends well and almost escapes with a draw, but
unfortunately for him, he blundered in an equal endgame later on.} 62. Kf3 Bc5
63. Bh7 c3 64. Kg4 Bf2 65. Bg8+ Kc6 66. Bb3 Kd7 67. Kf3 Be1 68. g4 Bd2 69. Ke4
Ke7 70. Kf5 Be3 71. g5 hxg5 72. Kxg5 Bd2 73. Kg4 Be3 74. Kf3 Bd2 75. h6 gxh6
76. f5 c2 $4 (76... Bg5 $1 $11) 77. f6+ $1 $18 {This is what Dominguez missed}
Kf8 78. Bxc2 Bc3 79. Kf4 h5 80. Bd1 h4 81. Bg4 Ba5 82. Kf5 Bc7 83. e6 Bd8 84.
Bh5 h3 85. Bg4 h2 86. Bf3 Kg8 87. Kg6 Kf8 88. Bc6 1-0

