{[%evp 0,51,29,29,28,-24,0,0,-16,-40,-21,-11,-3,-12,-19,-45,-21,-33,0,-21,3,25,
10,2,2,-47,-27,-58,-15,-11,0,31,120,58,77,-56,113,120,84,115,135,113,121,154,
157,160,216,209,280,280,289,294,508,154]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 6. Ne5 {!} Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O {This is the main tabya in
the 5...Bd7 line. Black exchanged his light-squared bishop but gained few
tempis. White should lose some time to take the c4-pawn back.} Qd7 9. e3 O-O-O
{The most aggressive setup. Black wants to play h7-h5, followed by Nd5, f7-f5,
h5-h4, and g7-g5 with an attack. Obviously, after some calm development with
Be7 and 0-0, White simply wins back the c4- pawn and gets a comfortable
advantage thanks to the g2 bishop.} 10. Nd2 $5 {One of the main ideas for
White in "Open Catalan" is to take the pawn on c4 with the knight. This saves
a few tempos and If Black plays passively, then White will have an advantage.}
(10. Qa4 {after which Black plays} Nd5 11. Qxc4 h5 {followed by h5-h4 and
f7-f5, g7-g5 and Qh7. The position is quite interesting and practice proves
that Black's setup shouldn't be underestimated. Black scored some nice wins in
this line.}) 10... e5 $1 11. Nxc4 exd4 12. Qa4 {Novelty at the time} (12. exd4
Qe6 {is the old line}) 12... d3 $6 {Black solves the tension in the center,
but also gives White a free hand to build an attack. Black is a pawn up, but
with queens on the board, the vulnerability of White's king is a decisive
factor.} (12... Bc5 {deserves attention} 13. b4 $1 {White should continue
playing actively. The position is quite complicated and I decide not to dig
deep in the theory. For those who are interested in this line I suggest
Davorin Kuljasevic's database for Modern Chess}) 13. Rd1 Bc5 14. Bd2 Nd5 15.
Rac1 Kb8 16. Qb3 Qe6 17. Ne5 $1 {A very strong move which forces favorable
exchanges for White.} Bb6 (17... Nxe5 18. Rxc5 c6 19. e4 {seems to win a piece
on the spot, because after trading the queens the e5 is hanging, but Black has}
) 18. Nxc6+ bxc6 19. Rc4 {The threat is to play Rdc1 or a4-a5.} c5 (19... Ka8
20. Rdc1 $18) 20. Re4 Qd6 21. a4 Nb4 22. Bxb4 cxb4 23. Rxb4 Qc5 24. Rb5 Qc2 25.
a5 {This move just finishes the game} c6 26. Rb4 {Black resigned.} 1-0

