{[%evp 0,73,29,15,23,0,20,44,29,33,45,16,21,13,-9,-6,72,68,57,4,28,16,56,21,35,
3,43,11,76,74,73,22,72,55,50,48,52,47,95,86,78,71,62,71,92,58,95,74,60,47,85,
70,108,93,88,83,106,127,152,162,172,142,122,122,116,152,157,183,203,168,233,
211,230,243,279,339] This is our model game for the b2-b3 idea.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4
c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 dxc4 6. Bg2 b5 7. Ne5 a6 8. O-O Bb7 {We have a
typical Catalan type of position. The pawn on c4 is well defended. White needs
to prove compensation. The typical idea in this type of positions is b2-b3!
Remember that this idea is almost always good in Catalan, If Black had already
committed to b7-b5.} 9. b3 $1 cxb3 10. axb3 {Sometimes Qxb3 is also possible.
White has good compensation for the two semi-open files. Black should try to
play c6-c5 and to open the position, even if White takes the pawn back. If
Black plays passively, then White just finishes the development, and takes
full control of c5-square. Afterwards, he can try to play in the centre or on
the kingside.} Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Qc2 Nfd7 ({If} 12... Qxd4 {then} 13. Nd5 Qc5
14. Qxc5 Bxc5 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Ng4 $16) (12... Nbd7 $1 {was tried in other
games and Black has no problems} 13. Bxc6 (13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bxc6 Rc8 $17) (13.
Nd3 $5 {with similar motifs to the game, but now Black's pieces are more
naturally placed}) 13... Qc7 $15) 13. Nd3 $1 {Very strong move. Now it is
clear that White has more than enough compensation in this position, mainly
thanks to his more active pieces. All Black's pieces on the queenside are very
passive} Qb6 14. Ne4 $1 {taking control of the c5-square.} a5 $5 {the idea is
Na6-b4} 15. Ndc5 Bc8 (15... Nxc5 16. dxc5 Qc7 17. Qc3 {with large advantage}) (
15... Nf6 $5) 16. Qc3 {A very tricky move. White provokes b5-b4. After that,
Black's knight can't go to b4 and White has the c4-square at his disposal.} b4
17. Qe3 Na6 18. Rfc1 {Kramnik decides to keep the rook on the a-file.} Nc7 19.
Nxd7 $1 {Important positional idea. Both White's knights want to go to c5, so
Kramnik exchange one of them and takes the square with the another one.} Bxd7
20. Nc5 Be8 (20... Bxc5 $4 {This exchange is always bad!} 21. dxc5 $18) 21. Ra2
{Typical Kramnik! Black has no counterplay and White improves his position.
White should double the rooks on "c" or "a" file.} Qb5 22. Qd3 {Another
interesting positional decision. It seems that Black's most active piece is
the queen, so Kramnik exchanges it. Even with a pawn down, White is better in
the arising endgame.} Qxd3 23. Nxd3 Nd5 24. Ne5 Ra6 (24... c5 $5 {I like this
pawn sacrifice. At least Black's pieces are naturally placed now} 25. dxc5 Bb5
{[%cal Rf8c8]}) 25. Bf1 $1 {Another typical Catalan maneuvre. Quite often,
when the diagonal h1-a8 is blocked, White activates the bishop via f1. White
is threatening e2-e4.} Nc3 $2 {Black returned the pawn. Nevertheless, it would
have been better to sacrifice the c-pawn. Now the material is equal, but the
weaknesses on "c6" and "a5" are still there.} (25... Ra7 $5 {Black should play
this natural move and continue suffering.}) 26. Bxc3 bxc3 27. Rxc3 c5 {
Probably Giri was in time trouble, but it seems to me that he just lost the
track of the game.} 28. dxc5 {Now White is completely winning.} Bf6 29. f4 Bb5
30. Bg2 Ra7 31. c6 Be7 32. Be4 f6 33. Nf3 Rd8 34. e3 e5 35. fxe5 fxe5 36. Rc1
a4 $2 {the last mistake from Giri} 37. bxa4 {after this simple move Giri
resigned. A positional masterpiece by GM Kramnik which I think is the absolute
model game for White in this structure.} 1-0

