{[%evp 0,105,18,23,28,-16,-11,-16,-16,-40,-7,-10,11,-18,14,-6,-17,2,6,3,7,-21,
36,30,27,33,54,20,25,19,43,35,13,17,19,-1,27,7,9,-8,-12,-2,9,0,-3,-2,3,15,13,
13,14,14,15,-1,17,16,10,15,15,26,25,6,9,37,64,40,40,37,39,35,24,-34,-12,-18,
-18,-18,7,7,13,13,13,-145,-145,-128,0,0,0,0,0,-177,-49,-33,-101,-81,-63,-154,
-136,0,242,242,318,318,29981,29982,29993,29994,29995,29996]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 {Very popular line
nowadays.} 8. Bg5 (8. Ne5 {is the main line} Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 {Black has
pretty decent results in this variation}) 8... Nd5 (8... Bb7 $4 {is a
well-known mistake} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Ng5 Bxg5 11. Bxb7 Nd7 12. Bxa8 {1-0 (24)
Cheparinov,I (2677)-Bekker Jensen,S (2466) Sibenik 2016}) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbd2
{We see again the situation where White wants to take the pawn with the knight.
If Black allows that, then White will be much better.} (10. Qxc4 {was also
possible}) 10... b5 $1 {Black needs to protect the pawn.} 11. b3 $1 {The same
sacrifice as in Kramnik's game} cxb3 (11... c3 {is principled} 12. Ne4 b4 13.
a3 {with a very complicated position}) 12. Nxb3 {This time White takes with
the knight. Again the c5-square is very weak. Additionally, the c7-pawn is
another major problem.} a5 13. Rfc1 a4 {The idea is to stop a2-a4, but I don't
like this. Now the structure on the queenside is not flexible and White has
one extra square (b4) for his pieces.} 14. Nc5 c6 15. Ne5 f6 {An important
moment, now Black's structure on the queenside is weakened} 16. Ned3 Rd8 17. e3
{It is very hard to suggest anything constructive for Black} Ra7 18. a3 Nd7 19.
Qa2 Nxc5 20. Rxc5 Bd7 21. Rac1 Be8 22. Qb2 Qd6 23. Nb4 Nxb4 24. Qxb4 Re7 {
It is very interesting that White can take the pawn back whenever he wants,
but of course Gledura decided to keep the tension.} 25. Qb2 Rc7 26. f4 {
From now until the end of the game Gledura played quite instructively. Black
has no counterplay and now White provokes weaknesses on the kingside and then
starts rolling his pawns. The principle of two weaknesses in action.} Rb8 {
It is very interesting that the engines evaluate the position as equal, but
for us is quite easy to realize that Black is dead lost} 27. Be4 Rb6 28. Qc2 {
White provokes more weaknesses} g6 29. Qc3 Ra7 30. h4 Kg7 31. g4 Re7 32. g5 (
32. h5 $1 e5 33. dxe5 fxe5 34. Kf2 {and White is much better}) 32... e5 $1 33.
dxe5 fxe5 34. Bf3 Kg8 35. Rd1 Qb8 36. Rxe5 b4 $1 {Black is fighting hard} 37.
axb4 Rxe5 38. fxe5 Rxb4 39. Bxc6 Bf7 40. Bd5 Bxd5 41. Rxd5 Rg4+ 42. Kh2 Rxh4+ (
42... Qf8 $3 {and the computer gives 0.00. Nevertheless, humans are not
capable to find such geometries.} 43. Qd2 Qf5 44. Rd8+ Kg7 $11) 43. Kg3 $18 Rh5
44. Kg4 $4 (44. Qc4 $3 $18) 44... h6 45. e6 hxg5 46. e7 Rh4+ 47. Kf3 Rh3+ 48.
Ke2 Rh2+ (48... Kf7 $3 $11) 49. Kd3 Qb1+ 50. Kd4 Rh4+ 51. Kc5 Re4 52. Rd8+ Kf7
53. Rf8+ {White won a very instructive game. Even though there are some
adventures at the end of the game.} 1-0

