{[%evp 0,83,23,23,28,-16,-16,-14,-4,-40,-21,-52,-5,0,6,-31,-22,1,10,0,11,5,48,
58,41,21,29,27,38,36,25,17,24,16,26,18,11,14,34,46,75,86,51,58,68,60,70,73,73,
73,73,73,78,89,137,117,110,84,113,106,120,120,121,101,107,107,110,85,110,117,
142,117,173,139,196,196,191,284,276,210,493,508,525,542,577,578] If you want
to learn the latest trends in Catalan, I suggest you follow the games of GM R.
Wojtaszek.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 {Interesting
line, which was quite popular a few years ago. Black's idea is to play Bc6 and
to oppose the bishop on g2.} 6. O-O (6. Ne5 {is the mainline which you can see
in the next game.}) 6... Bc6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 (7... b5 {Is the most principle move
here.}) 8. Qxc4 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Re1 {White is threatening to play e4.} Bxf3
{Quite a typical idea. A similar structure arised in Grischuk - Dominguez game.
} 11. Bxf3 c6 12. Bg2 {The main difference between this position and
Grishcuk's game is that White didn't weaken the b4-square. This detail
completely changes the evaluation of the position and we can conclude that
White is much better here.} Qa5 13. Rd1 Rfd8 14. Qb3 Qb6 15. Qc2 Rac8 16. h3 h6
17. Rb1 {White just improves the position before starting any concrete actions.
As we know both "c6-c5" and "e6-e5" breaks are not very useful for Black,
because then White's light-squared bishop will be very active.} Nf8 18. Na4 Qa6
19. b4 {winning even more space. Now one idea could be e2-e3 followed by Bf1
or immediately Nc5.} b5 $6 {This is a positional mistake but, understandably,
Mamedov wanted to play something active.} 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. bxc5 $18 {The game
is strategically over. White has a space advantage, bishop pair and the
d6-pawn is weak. The most obvious plan for me is Bf4-d6 followed by a2-a4 or
by advancing the kingside pawns.} e5 {Already a desperation} 22. dxe5 Rxd1+ 23.
Qxd1 N6d7 24. e6 $1 {Wojtaszek played brilliantly. Now the light squares in
Black's camp will be very weak.} fxe6 25. Qc2 Ne5 26. a4 Nc4 (26... Qxa4 27.
Qxa4 bxa4 28. Rb4 {looks winning for White}) 27. Kh2 {Tigran Vartanovich will
be proud of this move. Prophylactic before all.} Qa5 28. axb5 cxb5 29. c6 {
The passed c6-pawn will decide the game. The rest is a simple technique and
the Polish GM converts his advantage without any troubles.} a6 30. Bf4 Qa3 31.
Rd1 Qc5 32. Be3 Qe7 33. Bd4 Qe8 34. Qe4 Qe7 35. Bc3 Qf7 36. Qd4 Ng6 37. Ra1 a5
38. Bxa5 Ne7 39. Bc3 Nxc6 40. Bxc6 Rxc6 41. Ra8+ Kh7 42. Qe4+ 1-0

