[FEN "2rq1rk1/p2nbppp/bp3n2/2pp4/2PP4/1P3NP1/PBQN1PBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[PlyCount "55"]
[EventDate "1958.??.??"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "13"]
[EventCountry "URS"]
[SourceTitle "EXT 2010"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "2010.11.25"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2010.11.25"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{In the first three examples, the main theme is the connection between the
central tension and the kingside attacking chances. We have a typical
situation with a massive central tension. One of the first dynamic ideas I
became familiar with as a kid was that in such situations none of the sides
should release the tension too soon, as this would allow the enemy pieces to
become more active by occupying the squares previously occupied by pawns. [#]} 
13. Rfe1 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gd4,Gd5] From the point of view of the ideas expressed
above, this is the right policy. White continues developing and kindly invites
Black to release the tension himself.} cxd4 $6 {... which he kindly did! This
move increases the activity of none less than three white minor pieces, namely
both bishops and the king's knight.} (13... dxc4 $2 {would also be premature.}
14. bxc4 {After Black cleared the d5-square, White threatens to gain space
with d4-d5.} cxd4 15. Nxd4 $16 {[%csl Gc6] Black faces serious problems with
defending c6.}) (13... Re8 $5 {was correct, inviting White to prove that he
still has neutral useful moves.}) 14. Nxd4 Bb4 {This will result in a loss of
a tempo, which does not change the evaluation of the position, as a2-a3 is not
that useful for White at this stage. Black's main idea is to remove the bishop
from the vulnerable square, as White was obviously planning to play Nf5.} (
14... b5 15. Nf5) (14... Bc5 {leads to similar play as in the game.}) 15. a3
Bc5 (15... Bxd2 16. Qxd2 dxc4 17. Nf5 $18 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf5e7] with such
threats as Ne7+, Qg5, or simply Rad1 leaves Black desperately passive.}) 16.
Nf5 Re8 {It goes without saying that since Black intended to develop his rook,
he should have done it before releasing the tension, as suggested above.} (
16... Ng4 {offers White a choice.} 17. Rf1 {This may be simplest. The knight
on g4 may be hanging and g7 is under attack.} (17. Bxg7 $5 {This weakens the
enemy kingside but has the drawback of leading to simplifications.} Bxf2+ 18.
Kh1 Bxe1 19. Bxf8 Qxf8 (19... Bxd2 $2 20. Be7 $18) 20. Rxe1 Re8 21. Rxe8 Qxe8
22. Nf3 dxc4 23. Qd2 {The position remains very dangerous for Black but he can
hope to reach a just worse ending.}) 17... dxc4 18. Nxc4 f6 19. Rad1 $16) (
16... g6 {leads to similar play as in the game, but as surprising as it may
seem, with an extra tempo for White.} 17. Bxd5 $1 gxf5 (17... Nxd5 18. Nh6#)
18. Qxf5 {Black would need to play both ... Re8 and ...Bf8 to reach the later
game position.} Be7 (18... Re8 19. Ne4) 19. Re4 Nxe4 (19... Rc5 20. Rh4 {
[%cal Gf5g5,Gg5h6,Gh4g4]}) 20. Bxe4 $18) 17. Nxg7 $1 {This is the first
important tactical moment. White sacrifices a knight on one of the vulnerable
dark squares mentioned in the introduction.} Kxg7 18. Bxd5 $1 {This
corresponds to the second scenario described above. The bishop takes f7 under
observation. However, we should mention that the immediate purpose of this
move is to prepare Qf5 without fearing ...d5-d4, which would obstruct the
b2-bishop.} (18. Qf5 d4) 18... Kg8 19. Qf5 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 {[%csl Ga6] White
has only two pawns for the piece, but the bishop on a6 does not count for much
and the rook on c8 is also far from the main theatre of action. White can win
at leisure.} Bf8 21. Ne4 Bg7 22. Bxf7+ $5 (22. Ng5 $18) (22. Nd6 $18) 22... Kh8
(22... Kxf7 23. Ng5+ Kg8 (23... Kf8 24. Ne6+) 24. Qe6+) 23. Ng5 {[%csl Rf6,Gh7]
} Qf8 24. Bd5 Rb8 25. Re6 Bc8 26. Re8 $5 Qxe8 27. Nf7+ Qxf7 28. Bxf7 Bb7 29.
Be6 Re8 30. f3 Nf8 31. Qxf6 Nxe6 32. Qf7 Bc6 33. Bf6 Bxf6 34. Qxf6+ Kg8 35. h4
Ba8 36. h5 a5 37. h6 Bc6 38. f4 Bd7 39. f5 Rf8 40. Qe5 1-0

