{The e5-pawn ensures White a space advantage and possibilities to set up
pressure on both wings. Organizing a kingside attack would be easier with a
stable centre, so Black decided to break with ...c6-c5. True, this will force
him to somewhat weaken his kingside defence at least temporarily. [#]} 13... b5
14. Ne3 c5 15. Qg4 Kh8 16. dxc5 Nxc5 {An important decision. Black keeps his
bishop on e7 in order to control g5, but as beautifully as the knight seems to
be standing on c5, it does not have favourable paths in the future.} (16...
Bxc5 {may have been safer (though not necessarily better objectively). Black
would clear e7 for the queen and put some latent pressure on f2.} 17. Nxd5 Bxd5
18. Qh5 (18. Rd1 f6 $1 {leaves White with problems along the f-file.}) 18...
Kg8 19. Bxh6 gxh6 20. Qxh6 Qe7 21. Ng5 f6 22. Qg6+ {Black has a choice between
accepting a perpetual check and continue playing in an unclear ending after}
Qg7 23. Qxg7+ Kxg7 24. Bxd5 exd5 25. Ne6+ Kf7 26. Nxf8 Nxe5 27. Nh7 Rh8 28.
Nxf6 Kxf6) 17. Rd1 Qe8 $1 {The best defence. Black maintains the possibility
of meeting Qh5 with ... f7-f6.} (17... Qb6 {could cause unexpected problems:}
18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Be3 {A perfect square for the bishop. While Bxh6 remains an
issue, the pressure on c5 and the newly created pin could cause problems on
the other wing, too.} Qb7 (19... a5 20. Qh5 Rad8 21. Rac1 b4 22. Rd4 {
Threatening Bxh6 with a quick win.} Bxf3 23. Qxf3 Rxd4 24. Bxd4 {The bishops'
pressure ensures White a consistent advantage. The knight is obviously
misplaced.}) 20. Rxd5 $1 {A thematic exchange sacrifice, forcing Black to
weaken his kingside light squares.} exd5 (20... Qxd5 21. Nd4 Qd7 22. Bc6 Qc8
23. Bxa8 Qxa8 24. Nxb5 $16 Qb7 25. Qc4 a6 26. Nd6 Qxb2 $2 27. Bd4) 21. Nd4 Rad8
22. Nf5 Ne6 23. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 24. Qh5 Rd7 25. Rd1 Bc5 26. Qxh6+ Kg8 27. b4 $1 {
Overloading the bishop, which cannot control both e7 and d4 anymore.} Bb6 (
27... Bxb4 28. Rd4) 28. Rxd5 $1) 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Be3 a5 20. Qh5 (20. Rxd5 {
remains interesting, but Black seems to be able to hold his own:} exd5 21. Nd4
Rd8 22. Nf5 Ne6 23. Bb6 (23. Bxh6 gxh6 24. Qh5 f6 $1 {The point behind the
mysterious queen move.} 25. Qxh6+ Kg8 26. Bf3 Qf7 27. Bh5 Qh7 28. Qxh7+ Kxh7
29. Nxe7 d4 {with just good white compensation for the exchange.}) 23... Rd7
24. Rd1 Qb8 25. Rxd5 (25. Bxa5 Bc5) 25... Rxd5 26. Bxd5 Qxb6 27. Bxe6 Bg5 28.
Bd5 g6 {White retains good compensation for the exchange, but probably not an
advantage.}) 20... Be4 21. Nd4 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Rd8 23. Rac1 Rd5 {Geometrically,
Black's play looks inspiring, but his central pieces are hanging a bit. White
will use this aspect to add tension to the game.} 24. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 25. Qxh6+
Kg8 26. Nf5 {In some lines above, White sacrificed on d5 in order to get the
f5-square for his knight. Now the process is reversed, but each time the pawn
on e6 is overloaded.} exf5 27. Rxd5 Qa8 28. Qd2 {White has a small material
advantage, but also some problems of coordination, as the rook on d5 is pinned
and a bit hanging. Should he solve these, he would have better chances in the
endgame.} Rd8 $2 {An excusable blunder as White's small combination is a bit
unusual... Black should have found a good square for his knight but this is
not that simple.} (28... Ne4 $6 29. Qd1 {[%cal Gf2f3] Threatening f2-f3.} Nc5
30. Kh2 Ne6 31. Qd3 $16) (28... Ne6 $6 29. Kh2 Kg7 30. Rd7 Rd8 31. Rxd8 Bxd8 (
31... Qxd8 32. Qxd8 Bxd8 33. f4 b4 34. Rc6 $16) 32. Qd3) (28... a4 $1 29. Kg1
Ne4 30. Qd1 a3 31. b3 b4 {AFter ensuring the c3-square for the knight black
should be doing fine.}) 29. Rcxc5 $1 (29. Rcxc5 Bxc5 30. Qg5+ {[%cal Gg5d8]
The combination is a schematic illustration of White's earlier planning. It
all started in the centre, then play switched to the kingside, and then to the
centre again.}) 1-0

