{The next two examples illustrate the way White can build up a kingside attack
with a stable centre. White has a space advantage and Black should find a way
of breaking with ...c6-c5. The next two examples illustrate the way White can
build up a kingside attack with a stable centre.} 15... Nc4 $2 {This only
helps White bringing his knight on a better square. [#]} (15... c5 $1 16. Nxc5
Nxc5 17. dxc5 Nc4 $11) 16. Rc1 Nxe3 17. Nxe3 {[%csl Gd5] Even if Black manages
to sustain his c-pawn for advancing, White will always have the strong answer
d4-d5, making full use of the knight's placement on e3.} Rc8 18. e5 {With the
centre stable, White can prepare his attack at leisure.} Rc7 19. Qg4 {[%csl
Gd4,Gg7]} Rd7 20. Rfd1 Qa5 21. b3 Rc8 (21... c5 22. d5 $16) 22. h4 Qd8 {
White has pressure on both wings, but winning is not trivial yet.} 23. Kh2 $5 {
A half-waiting move, which will act as a provocation.} g6 $6 {Preparing the
queen's transfer to h6, but offering White a clear target.} (23... Qe8 24. Rc4
Nc7 25. Nc5 (25. Bxc6 $6 Bxc6 26. Rxc6 Rxd4) 25... Bxc5 26. Rxc5 $16) 24. h5
Qf8 25. hxg6 Qh6+ {Black could not resist the temptation of "gaining two
tempi".} 26. Kg1 hxg6 27. Be4 Qg5 28. Qf3 Nb8 29. Kg2 {This time, the king's
advance has a clear purpose. The rook will soon occupy the h-file. With his
queen's knight and bishop busy elsewhere, Black does not have satisfactory
defences.} (29. Nc5 $16) 29... Rcd8 30. Rh1 $1 {Preparing a beautiful
combination.} Rxd4 31. Rh8+ $1 Kxh8 32. Qxf7 Rd1 33. Rxd1 Rxd1 34. Nxd1 Qxe5 (
34... Nd7 35. f4 Qg4 36. Nf2 {/\ Qe7}) 35. Qe8+ 1-0

