{This is one more example about how White can prepare his kingside attack when
the centre is stable. The main issue is being permanently prepared against ...
c6-c5. [#]} 23. Be4 Rfd8 24. Qh5 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5] Controlling both c5 and e5.}
Na2 25. Rc2 Nb4 26. Rcd2 Nd5 27. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Gc3]} (27. Bb1 Nc3 $132) (27.
Bc2 Nc3 28. Rc1 b5 $132) 27... Qa7 {[%cal Ga7b8] Black needs to remain passive.
} (27... b5 28. Ne5 $14) 28. Bb1 ({In view of the line recommended below,
White should have still improved his position with, say,} 28. Kg2 {leaving his
bishop on e4 still. The counterplay examined in the next line does not work
out well here:} c5 29. Ne5 Bxe5 30. Qxe5 Qb6 31. dxc5 Qxb3 32. Rd4 {[%cal
Gc1d1]} Qa2 33. Rc2 Qa3 34. g4 $40) 28... Ne7 ({But now the thematic break} 
28... c5 {looks possible:} 29. Ne5 Bxe5 30. Qxe5 Qb6 $132 {[%csl Gb3] If not
sustaining a kingside attack, the white bishop could well be passive and
vulnerable.} 31. dxc5 Qxb3 32. Rd4 Qa3 33. Rcd1 Qb3 {White would like to
increase the pressure against d5 with Be4 but this is not easy to achieve:} 34.
Kg2 (34. Be4 $2 Nxe3 $1 {wins based on} 35. Rxd7 Qxd1+ 36. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 37. Kh2
Ng4+) (34. g4 $2 {is met in the same way:} Nxe3 $1 35. fxe3 Qxd1+ 36. Rxd1
Rxd1+ 37. Kf2 R8d2+ 38. Kf3 Rf1+ 39. Kg3 Rxb1 $19) 34... Qb2 {and once again}
35. Be4 $2 {allows} Nxe3+) 29. Rdd1 ({Eljanov must have wished to achieve a
bit more than after} 29. Qxa5 Qxa5 30. Nxa5 e5 31. Nc4 exd4 32. e4 $14) 29...
Rd5 30. Qf3 R5d7 31. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4]} Kf8 $2 {We are still far from the
endgame so this king's "centralising" is likely to cause only problems if
carried out without a serious reason. Adams wanted to anticipate the threat
Qe4 and clear the g8-square for his knight, but there was no need for that.} (
31... Nd5 $5 32. Qe4 (32. Ne4 Be7 {maintains the status quo.}) 32... Kf8 $1 {
Now that White has committed himself by occupying the e4-square with the queen,
this is good and necessary.} (32... g6 $2 33. h5 $18) 33. Kg2 Qb8 34. Qh7 $6 g6
$1 {[%csl Gh7]} 35. Qxh6+ (35. Be4 Bg7 {[%cal Gd5f6]} 36. Bxd5 Rxd5 $11) 35...
Ke7 {[%cal Gd8h8]} 36. Bxg6 fxg6 37. Ne4 Rh8 38. Qxg6 Rg8 $11) 32. Ne4 Ng8 {
This surely looks passive,} ({but the more natural} 32... Nd5 {causes Black
problems of stability.} 33. Nc5 Rd6 34. Kg2 $3 {By removing the king from the
back rank, White creates some additional tactical ideas. Besides, Black is in
a sort of zugzwang with all his pieces on the board.} (34. e4 Nc7 35. e5 Bxe5
36. Nxb7 Qxb7 37. dxe5 Rxd1+ {With check!} 38. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 39. Qxd1 Nd5 $11)
34... Be7 (34... Kg8 35. e4 Nc7 36. e5 Bxe5 37. dxe5 Rxd1 38. Rxd1 Rxd1 39.
Qxd1 Qxc5 40. Qd8+ {and Black does not have ... Ne8.}) (34... Qb6 $2 35. e4 Nc7
36. e5 Bxe5 37. dxe5 Rxd1 38. Rxd1 Rxd1 39. Bg6 $18) (34... Ke8 $5 {,
controlling the d7- and d8-squares and getting the king out of the potential
pin along the f-file, is interesting but hardly satisfactory.} 35. h5 $16) 35.
e4 Nf6 (35... Nc7 36. e5 Rxd4 37. Bg6 f6 38. exf6 Bxf6 39. Rxd4 Rxd4 40. g4 $18
) 36. Qe3 (36. e5 Rxd4) 36... Qb8 37. Ba2 $3 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gb3b4,Ge4e5]
Even if I needed some time to understand the idea behind this move, I am not
sure if it would be right to call it a computer move. It is just a pity we
could not offer this position as a test to some of the greates champions of
the past, but my guess is that at least some of them would find it.} (37. e5
Rd5 $1) 37... b6 (37... Qc8 38. e5 Rd5 39. b4 $18 Bxc5 40. bxc5) 38. e5 Nd5 39.
Qf3 bxc5 40. exd6 Bxd6 41. dxc5 Be5 42. Bb1 $18) 33. Nc5 Rd6 34. Bd3 Be7 35.
Bc4 Nf6 36. g4 $36 {After some more regrouping moves, White has finally
started his kingside attack. Obviously, the king does not stand well on f8.} b6
37. Nd3 (37. Nxe6+ fxe6 38. g5 Kg8 39. gxf6 Bxf6 40. h5 $14) 37... Nd7 38. Nf4
Kg8 39. Qg3 Qb8 $6 (39... Nf6 {would have been more active:} 40. Bd3 (40. g5
hxg5 41. hxg5 Ne4) 40... Nd5 $14) 40. g5 hxg5 41. hxg5 b5 {Just a hint of
black counterplay.} 42. Bd3 e5 43. Ne2 g6 44. Kg2 exd4 45. e4 $6 {There was no
need to sacrifice a pawn.} (45. Qh4 Bf8 46. Nxd4 $16) 45... Kf8 $2 {The second
centralisation of the king should have had fatal consequences.} (45... Bf8 $5
$13) 46. Rh1 (46. axb5 cxb5 {[%csl Gd5]} 47. Qh4 Ke8 48. Qh8+ Nf8 49. Nf4 $18)
(46. Qh4 $18) 46... Ke8 47. Rh8+ Bf8 48. axb5 {This absolves Black from the
worries regarding his c6-pawn, but opens the c-file. As we will see by
comparing the two similar lines below, the exchange does not alter the overall
evaluation in any way.} (48. Qf4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gh8h7]} Re6 49. Qxb8
Nxb8 {[%csl Gd4]} (49... Rxb8 50. Nxd4 Rd6 51. Nxc6 Rb6 52. Bxb5 $18) 50. axb5
cxb5 51. Bxb5+ Ke7 52. Rc7+ Kd6 (52... Nd7 53. Nxd4) 53. Rxf7 $18) 48... cxb5
49. e5 (49. Qf4 {is still very strong, even though play changes a bit with
respect to the similar line above.} Re6 50. Rc7 $1 {Taking advantage of the
previous opening of the c-file.} (50. Qxb8 Rxb8 $16 51. Nxd4 $2 Rd6 52. Nc6 Rb6
{and White does not have Bxb5 anymore.}) 50... Qb6 51. Qc1 $1 $18) 49... Rd5
50. Qf4 $2 {Losing a second pawn without compensation.} (50. Re1 $3 Rc8 (50...
Rxe5 51. f4 {[%cal Ge2d4,Rg3e1]}) (50... Nxe5 51. Nxd4 $18) (50... Qxe5 51. Nf4
Qxe1 52. Nxd5 $18) 51. Kf1 $3 (51. e6 Qxg3+ 52. Nxg3 Ne5 53. Be4 {is also
strong, but the king retreat prepares the intermediate move exd7+.}) 51... Qc7
52. e6 Qxg3 (52... fxe6 53. Nf4 $18) 53. exd7+ Kxd7 54. Nxg3 $18) 50... Qxe5
$15 51. Re1 $2 {Beter late than never does not apply here.} (51. Qxe5+ Nxe5 52.
Be4 R5d6 53. f4 Nd7 54. Bd3 Ke7 55. Bxb5 $2 d3 $17) 51... Qxh8 $19 52. Nxd4+
Re5 53. Rh1 Qg7 54. Bxb5 Be7 55. Ba4 Rxg5+ 56. Kf1 Qe5 57. Qxe5 Rxe5 58. Rh8+
Bf8 59. Nc6 Rh5 0-1

