{In the next two examples, Black took on c4 and defended his extra pawn,
leaving White an advantage in the centre. The king's presence in the centre
can add spice to the fight for the central squares. Here is an example which
had inspired me when starting to play the Catalan, almost three decades ago. 
[#]} 10. e4 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4 Bd4+ 14. Be3 Bc6 $2 {As the
game shows, Black is not in a position to maintain the piece tension. He
should have chosen one of the continuations below, even though White has more
than enough compensation for the pawn.} (14... Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3) (14... c5 15. e5
) 15. e5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxe3 (16... Bxc3 17. exf6 Qd5+ 18. Kg1 Bxf6 19. Bc5+ {
wins}) 17. exf6 $1 (17. Qxe3 Nd5 18. Qe4 Nxc3 19. Qc6+ Kf8 20. bxc3 $16) 17...
Qd2 {This was the move Black had relied on, but White has a mathematical win
now.} 18. Rf2 $1 O-O-O 19. Qg4+ Qd7 20. Qf3 {A nasty double attack.} Qd4 21.
Re2 (21. Rd1 Bxf2 $18) 21... Qxf6 (21... Rhe8 22. Rd1) 22. Rxe3 Kb8 23. Rae1
1-0

[Event "San Francisco 63/372"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1995.??.??"]
