{We will now examine two examples with symmetrical structure, meaning that
there are no pawns at all in the centre. White's better development can offer
him attacking chances in such cases. [#]} 11. Bg5 Rd8 (11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6
13. e3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1e2,Re6e5] Granda probably disliked having his
bishop restricted this way. One more problem is that preparing to complete the
queenside development with . ..e6-e5 would weaken the d5-square.}) 12. Qc1 Bd4
(12... h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Ne4 Qe7 15. Rd1 {makes clear Black's problems with
the development.}) 13. Ne4 $1 (13. e3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Bd7 $14) 13... h6 {Too
late to force White taking on f6.} 14. Bh4 $1 {An elegant way to maintain the
kingside tension.} Bd7 (14... g5 {offers White a decisive attack.} 15. Nxg5
hxg5 16. Qxg5+ Kf8 {There are many winning moves, most based on e2-e3. In fact,
} 17. e3 $5 {is the simplest.}) 15. Rd1 Be8 16. Qf4 {The fluence of White's
attack is [leasing from aesthetical point of view. The bishop has cleared c1
for the queen, which has later advanced to f4.} Qb4 (16... Rac8 17. e3) 17.
Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Rxd8 Nxd8 (19... Rxd8 20. Qxf6 Qxc4 $2 21. Bxc6
$18) 20. b3 {A queesnide move as an optimal complement to the kingside attack.}
(20. a3 $5 {would be similar from abstract point of view, but probably even
stronger.} Qb3 (20... Qa4 21. b4 Kg7 22. Nd6 $18) 21. Nd6 Qxb2 22. Rd1 $16 {
[%csl Ge8,Gf6,Gh6] The bishop and the pawns on h6 and f6 are hanging.} Qc2 $2
23. Rc1 $18) 20... Kg7 21. Rd1 Nc6 22. Qc7 a5 (22... Qe7 23. Qxe7 Nxe7 24. Bxb7
$16) 23. Nd6 a4 24. Bxc6 {The Catalan bishop finally plays a concrete part.}
bxc6 25. Qe7 1-0

