{Black is doing fine here, but it is instructive to follow how he gradually
offered White attacking chances. [#]} 17. Qc4 Qb6 (17... Qxc4 18. Nxc4 axb4 19.
Nb6 Rcd8 20. axb4 Nxb4 21. Ba3 Bc6 {WHite has reasonable compensation for the
pawn but not an advantage.}) 18. Qh4 {The switch to the kingside.} axb4 19. Nc4
Qc7 20. axb4 Nxb4 21. Nce5 Rfd8 $2 {In vain offering White a free tempo for
the attack.} (21... Bc6 $11) 22. Ng5 Be8 {It is obvious that White has
excellent attacking chances, but working out the concrete details is not
trivial.} 23. Rxd8 $2 {White should not have helped Black to bring his queen
on the h4-d8 diagonal.} (23. Ng4 $1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 h6 25. Nxf6+ Bxf6 26. Bxf6
gxf6 27. Ne4 $18) 23... Qxd8 $1 {[%csl Gf6]} 24. Ng4 h6 $2 {Missing an
excellent chance.} (24... Nh5 $1 25. Qxh5 Bxg5 $17 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf7f5]})
25. Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 26. Qxh6 {[%cal Gg5h7,Gg2e4] Due to the threats Nh7 and Be4
Black's position looks dangerous. However, he can still save the game.} Rc2 $1
(26... Bf8 27. Qh4 Bg7 28. Qxb4 $16 {Another line illustrating the connection
between the wings.}) 27. Be5 Rxe2 $2 {Overlooking the next move.} (27... Rc5 $1
{was the correct way to attack the bishop. White could agree to a draw by
repetition or still try} 28. Be4 Rxe5 29. Bh7+ Kh8 $11 {when he does not have
more than a perpetual.}) 28. Be4 $1 {The Catalan bishop joins the attack,
changing its initial direction of acting.} Rd2 29. Bh7+ Kh8 30. Bxf6+ Bxf6 31.
Qf8# {When analysing the game I overlooked this mate in one and calculated
only the known mechanism} (31. Bg6+ Kg8 32. Bxf7+ Bxf7 33. Qh7+ Kf8 34. Qxf7#)
1-0

