{This is the game I have used as a test beforethe Webinar. [#]} 22. c5 $1 {
White makes sure that Black does not break with ...c6-c5.} Qc8 (22... bxc5 23.
Bc7) 23. cxb6 Nxb6 24. Ne5 Nd5 25. Bd2 Rb5 26. Bc1 Rb3 27. Qc4 Nb6 28. Qc2 Nd5
29. Nd3 Ba6 30. Nc5 Bxc5 31. dxc5 Qb8 {Both sides seem to be well mobilized
and from structural point of view Black may seem top be doing fine. In the
game White found the Achille?s heel in Black?s position. How?} 32. Rd4 $1 {
Activating the rook with gain of time as the pawn on a4 is hanging.} Bb5 33.
Bxh6 $1 {Indeed, the less defended area is the kingside and White's chances
lie there. He should act without delay, as otherwise ...Nf6 would consolidate
Black's kingside.} (33. Rg4 Nf6 $11) 33... gxh6 34. Rg4+ Kf8 (34... Kh8 35. Qc1
Kh7 36. Rxe6 $5 fxe6 37. Be4+ Kh8 38. Qxh6#) 35. Qh7 {Threatening Rze6 among
others.} Ke7 (35... Bd3 {fails to insert the bishop into the defence.} 36.
Qxh6+ $1 Ke7 37. Rxe6+ $1 Kd7 (37... fxe6 38. Rg7+ {mates next.}) 38. Rg7 $5 {
All White's pieces are ready to attack the almost solitary king.}) 36. Rxe6+ $1
{The most convincing.} Kxe6 (36... Kd7 37. Qxf7+ Kc8 38. Rg8 $5 $18) 37. Re4+
Qe5 (37... Kf6 38. Qxh6+ Kf5 39. g4#) (37... Kd7 38. Qxf7+ Kc8 39. Bh3+) 38.
Bh3+ 1-0

