1. d4 Nf6 (1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {another version of catalan}) 2.
c4 e6 3. g3 d5 (3... c5 {The main drawback of 3.g3 move order is that Black
can try to enter Benoni.  Many White players are not happy to enter these
positions with White.} 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 (5... Bd6 {This is Snake Benoni,
I think White is just better here.}) (5... b5 {is another sideline, but I
think that White is better after 6.e4 or 6.Nf3} 6. e4 (6. Nf3 $5)) 6. Nc3 g6 7.
Bg2 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O {This is the starting position of g3  Benoni  I like this position for
White.}) (3... Bb4+ {Black can also play Bogo-Indian, but with the knight
still on g1, White has some additional options.} 4. Bd2 {Black has four
options here and all of them deserved attention.} a5 (4... c5 5. Bxb4 cxb4 6.
Bg2 O-O 7. e3 $5 {is a very interesting idea, White wants to play Ne2} (7. e4
d6 8. Ne2 e5 9. a3 {is the line which I proposed in my book}) 7... d6 8. Ne2 a5
9. O-O Na6 10. a3 $5 (10. Nd2 $5 $146 {Is a novelty which deserves a try})) (
4... Qe7 5. Nf3 (5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 {Is another line of
Bogo-Indian which I am trying to avoid}) 5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 7. b3 $5 {
the idea without complicated pawn sacrifice} (7. Nc3 {Is the mainline here} d5
8. Ne5 dxc4 9. Bg2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Qd4 $44 {very unclear}) (7. Bg2 $6 {
is a well known mistake} Ne4 {[%cal Ge7b4]}) 7... d5 $140 {This line seems
suspicios} 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O dxc4 $6 10. bxc4 e5 11. d5 Nb8 12. Qe3 Nbd7 13.
Nc3 $16) (4... Bxd2+ 5. Nxd2 (5. Qxd2 d5 6. Nf3 O-O {Is a nice line for Black.}
) 5... Nc6 (5... d6 6. e3 $5 {I recommended novelty, nowadays there are
already some games}) (5... d5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Ngf3 $14 {We are in some Catalan})
6. e3 (6. Ngf3 d6 7. e4 e5 $13) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 $14 {I don't like the knight
on "c6"}) 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 {We transpose to a theoretical position from
Catalan.} O-O (6... dxc4 7. Qc2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 (8. Nbxd2 {White can opt for the
b2-b3 sacrifice after.} b5 9. a4 c6 10. b3 cxb3 11. Nxb3 O-O 12. O-O $44 {
I don't believe White has more than just sufficient compensation}) 8... c6 9.
a4 b5 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Qg5 {Kramnik's idea} O-O 12. Qxb5 Ba6 (12... Na6 $6 13.
Qxc4 $14 {1-0 (102) Grischuk,A (2719)-Moiseenko,A (2662) Sochi 2006} (13. Nbd2
$5 $16)) 13. Qa4 (13. Qxa5 $140 {leads to an equal position} Bb7 14. Qxd8 Rxa1
$1 15. Qxf8+ Kxf8 16. O-O Ra2 $11) 13... Qb6 $1 14. O-O Qxb2 15. Nbd2 Bb5 16.
Nxc4 Bxa4 17. Nxb2 Bb5 18. Ne5 {This structure is not that simple. On many
occasions, White wins the pawn on "a5" and then the endgame is lost.} Ra7 (18...
Nd5 $5) 19. Nbd3 $14 (19. Bf3 Nbd7 20. Nec4 Rb8 21. Rfb1 g5 $1 $132 {Topalov
gets the initiative and refuses draw, but eventually lost 1-0 (75) Kramnik,V 
(2743)-Topalov,V (2813) Elista 2006})) 7. Qc2 (7. O-O dxc4 (7... b6 {We reach
Queen's Indian structure. Where White should be better.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5
Bb7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nc3 Rd8 (12... Bxc3 {is not equalizing as well
} 13. bxc3 Qd6 14. c4 $16) 13. Rc1 Na6 14. e3 Qe6 15. Nd3 Bd6 16. Qb3 $16))
7... c5 8. cxd5 (8. dxc5 d4 9. Bxb4 axb4 10. O-O Nc6 11. Nbd2 e5 12. Ng5 Qe7
13. Nge4 {this line is in my book} Nd7 $5 $146 14. Nb3 f5 15. Nd6 g6 16. Bxc6
bxc6 17. Qd2 Rb8 $44 {With a very complicated position in which I prefer
White 1/2-1/2 (55) Moreira, J (2406)-Obertin,F (2418) ICCF email 2012}) (8. O-O
{is not critical} cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Bc3 Bd7 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 $11) 8... cxd4 9.
Nxd4 Qb6 $1 {Black idea} 10. e3 exd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 Rb8 14.
Nc3 h5 15. h3 $5 $146 {is very interesting and I think that Black still needs
to solve some problems} (15. Na4 Qd8 16. Bxb4 Rxb4 17. b3 h4 18. Qxc6 h3 19.
Bh1 d4 $44 {And the Dutch GM outplayed his opponent 0-1 (34) Vidit,S (2726)
-Giri,A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020})) 4. Bg2 dxc4 {The Open Catalan is the
most ambitious try for Black} (4... Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O (6. Nc3 {Quite
trendy line popularized by F.Caruana} dxc4 (6... Nbd7 $5 7. Qd3 b6 {Aronian
line - Black transposes to Queen's Indian setup} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 (9. O-O
Bb7 10. Rd1 N7f6) 9... exd5 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 c5 12. b3 a5 $13 {White is
probably slightly better, but nothing special. The position is playable for
Black 1/2-1/2 (58) Grischuk,A (2777)-Aronian,L (2773) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 7.
Ne5 c5 (7... Nc6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 c5 12. dxc5
Qxc5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O-O $1 {amazing idea by Fabiano. There are a lot of
games in this line and it seems that it is not easy for Black to maintain the
ballance} Ng4 15. Rd2 Nxe3 16. fxe3 {1-0 (49) Caruana,F (2822)-Nakamura,H 
(2777) Saint Louis 2018}) 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 10. Ne3 (10. Bd2 Nd5 11.
Nxc4 Nc6 12. Rc1 {1-0 (68) Jumabayev,R (2609)-Karjakin,S (2753) Astana 2019}) (
10. O-O {main move}) 10... c3 11. bxc3 Nbd7 12. Nd3 {Dubov has three games
here, so this line deserves serious attention}) 6... dxc4 (6... c6 7. Qc2 b6 8.
b3 ({This was my preference for a long time, but now I found the line} 8. Nbd2
Bb7 9. e4 Na6 $1 {and Black is probably fine} (9... dxc4 $5 {another decent
option for Black} 10. Nxc4 Nbd7 {good line for Black} 11. Rd1 c5) (9... dxe4 {
very popular setup at a club level, but White is better here} 10. Nxe4) (9...
Nbd7 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Re1 {is a very promising for White.}) 10. a3
(10. e5 Nd7 11. cxd5 Nb4 $1 $11 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gc6c5]}) 10... c5 11. exd5 exd5
12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. b4 Ne6 14. Bb2 a5 $5 {Black has an excellent position}) 8...
Nbd7 (8... Bb7 9. Nc3) 9. Rd1 Bb7 10. Nc3 Ba6 $1 {the most challenging for
Black} (10... Rc8 11. e4 c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Bb2 $36 dxc4 (13... cxd4 14. Nxd4
$36 {[%cal Gg2b7]}) 14. d5 {[%cal Gd5d6]} cxb3 15. axb3 $16 {[%csl Ga7][%cal
Gd5d6]}) 11. e4 (11. Rb1 $5 Rc8 12. e4 dxc4 13. b4 Bb7 14. a4 $44 {1-0 (45)
Paravyan,D (2605)-Zhao,C (2379) Qingdao 2019}) 11... dxc4 12. e5 Nd5 13. bxc4
Bxc4 14. Ne4 b5 15. Neg5 g6 16. h4 $44 {The position looks dangerous for Black}
) 7. Qc2 (7. Qa4 $5 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 {transpose}) (7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Nxc6 (8. Bxc6
bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {good for Black}) 8... bxc6 9. Na3 $5 Bxa3 10.
bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 Rb8 12. Qa5 Qc8 (12... Rb6) 13. a4 Rd8 {Black is doing fine})
7... a6 (7... b5 8. a4 b4 (8... c6 $2 {is a well known mistake} 9. axb5 cxb5
10. Ng5 $1 h6 11. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 12. Bxa8 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qg4 14. Bf3 Qh3 15. Rxa7
$18) 9. Nfd2 (9. Ne5 Qxd4 10. Bxa8 Qxe5 $44 {scored extremely well for Black})
9... c6 (9... Nd5 10. Nxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Ba6 (11... Bxc5 12. e4 $5 $146 {still
novelty from my book} Nb6 13. Ncd2 $5 $14) 12. Ne3 Nd7 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. c6 Rc8
15. Bf4 Nc5 16. Rd1 (16. c7 Qd7 17. Nd2 g5 18. Be5 f6 19. Bd4 Rxc7 $132 {
0-1 (59) Ding,L (2805) -Carlsen,M (2875) Zagreb 2019}) 16... d4 17. h4 Re8 (
17... h6 18. Bf3 Re8 19. Nd2 Bf8 20. Nb3 {Another game}) 18. Nd2 Bxe2 19. c7
Qd7 20. Rdc1 {1-0 (33) Gelfand,B (2684)-Deac,B (2618) Bucharest 2019}) 10. Nxc4
Qxd4 11. Rd1 {Grischuk won a positional masterpiece in this line} Qc5 12. Be3
Qh5 13. Nbd2 Ng4 14. Nf3 $44 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 a5 16. Nd4 Ba6 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Bf3
Qg6 19. Be4 Qh5 20. Bf3 Qg6 21. Be4 Qh5 22. Kg2 Ra7 23. h4 $44 {1-0 (54)
Grischuk,A (2772)-Nakamura,H (2761) Moscow 2019}) (7... b6 $5 {Bukavshin
variation} 8. Bg5 (8. Ne5 Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 10. Bf3 Nd5 11. Qxc4 Ba6 12. Qa4 c5
$44 {Black is doing well in this line}) (8. Nfd2 {White can sacrifice a pawn
and has an obvious compensation, but probably not enough for an advantage.} c6
9. Nxc4 Qxd4 10. Rd1 Qc5 11. b3 Na6 12. Bb2 Bb7 13. a3 $44) 8... Nd5 9. Bxe7
Qxe7 10. Nbd2 b5 11. b3 c3 {The critical line} (11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 $44) 12.
Ne4 (12. e4 cxd2 13. exd5 exd5 14. Qxd2 $44 {[%csl Gc5,Gc7]}) 12... b4 13. a3
Nc6 14. axb4 Ncxb4 15. Qc1 Ba6 16. Re1 c2 17. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gf3e1]}) 8.
a4 (8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 Be4 (10... Bd6 {has very solid reputation})
11. Qc1 c6 {lately this is the most fashionable line} (11... Bb7 {is Karpov's
choice}) (11... Qc8 $5 {is another playable line})) 8... Bd7 (8... c5 9. dxc5
Bxc5 10. Qxc4 (10. Nbd2 b5 $1 11. axb5 Bb7 $44 {and Black is doing well}) 10...
b6 11. Ne5 Ra7 12. Nc3 (12. Nd3 Be7 13. Bf4 Bb7 $11) 12... Bb7 13. Bxb7 Rxb7
14. Ne4 $14 {White can play for a small advantage in this line}) 9. Qxc4 Bc6
10. Bf4 $1 {This is my favourite here} (10. Bg5 {is the main move, but I think
Black is doing fine}) 10... Bd6 (10... a5 {Is not equalizing} 11. Nc3 Na6 12.
Rac1 Nb4 13. Ne5 $14) 11. Qc1 Nbd7 (11... a5 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Rd1 {is the other
tree in this line}) 12. Nc3 (12. a5) 12... Qe7 13. a5 (13. Re1 {is not enough
for advantage} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 16. a5 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Bg2
Rad8 $11) 13... e5 (13... Rfe8 $5) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxe5
17. Qe3 Rfe8 18. Qxe5 Qxe5 19. Bxe5 Rxe5 {I think that White is better in this
endgame.} 20. Rfd1 (20. Ra4 $14) 20... Kf8 21. Ra4 $14 {1-0 (43) Fedoseev,V 
(2671) -Perez Ponsa,F (2559) chess.com INT 2020}) 5. Nf3 (5. Qa4+ $5 {This
variation always has drawish reputation} Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 7. Be3 Bd6 8. Qc2 (8.
Nh3 $5 {This move deserves attention and was tried by Ding Lieren}) 8... O-O 9.
Nh3 {White scores 2 out of 2 in this line. In the games So-Duda and Caruana -
Anand}) 5... a6 {This is the most ambitious line nowadays} 6. O-O (6. Ne5 {
was also possible}) 6... Nc6 {In this position White can play a lot of moves}
7. e3 (7. Nc3 Rb8 8. e4 {is a very complicated line in which White is doing OK}
) (7. Nbd2 $5 b5 $1 (7... Nxd4 $6 8. Nxc4 Nxf3+ 9. Bxf3 $14) 8. b3 {Is another
interesting option for White}) (7. Be3 {looks strange, but it is very tricky
the idea is to free the c1 square for the queen and to defend the "d4" pawn}
Nd5 8. Qc1 Be7 9. Qxc4 Nxe3 10. fxe3 O-O $13 {very interesting position with
mutual chances}) 7... Rb8 (7... Bd7 8. Qe2 b5 9. b3 $5 {Again the same idea. I
think with the bishop on d7 this sacrifice is quite strong.} cxb3 10. axb3 $44)
8. Nfd2 (8. Qe2 b5 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 $44 {There are many games in this line.
White definitely has compensation, but I am not sure that it is enough for
more than equal position} (10. Nfd2 $5 {Is an interesting option to try} Bb7
11. Nxb3 $44)) 8... e5 $1 {The most principled continuation} (8... Qd7 {
is a strange interesting move, but I think White is better} 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Ncd2
$14) (8... Bd7 {is another move which doesn't equalize} 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Ne5 $1
Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Nd2 $146 {Black's queenside is compromised, I think
White is just better in this line} Be7 13. b3 O-O 14. Ne4 c5 15. Bb2 c4 16. Qg4
g6 17. Rfd1) 9. Bxc6+ (9. Nxc4 exd4 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. exd4 Be7 12. Nc3 O-O $11
{The bishop pair fully compensate the weaken structure}) 9... bxc6 10. dxe5 Ng4
11. Nxc4 Be6 12. Nbd2 {Very sharp line, I do not recommend you to play this
with White if you are extremely well prepared. If you forgot the theory here,
just h5-h4 and mate!} Bb4 13. Qc2 $5 h5 14. b3 h4 $1 15. Nf3 hxg3 ({Amazing
computer move} 15... f5 $5 {1/2-1/2 (81) Jumabayev,R (2630) -Gelfand,B (2686)
Douglas 2019}) 16. fxg3 $1 Bc5 17. h4 (17. Kh1 $4 Qd7 18. Bd2 Bd5 19. e4 Qf5 $1
(19... Nxh2 $19) 20. h4 Bxe4 $19 {0-1 (23) Kim,Y (2360) -Matsenko,S (2533)
Sturbridge 2018}) 17... Rh5 {0-1 (26) Saduakassova,D (2519) -Ganguly,S (2636)
Wijk aan Zee 2020} 18. Kg2 {My engines prefer White, but the position remains
very complicated} *

