{[%csl Rc8,Gg2] [#] As pointed out in the introduction, the g2-bishop puts tremendous pressure on Black's queenside. Therefore, Black often fails to
develop his queenside pieces with accepting major concessions. If the
c8-bishop remains on its initial positions, White quickly achieves an
overwhelming advantage. His strategy, in this case, is quite simple - exchange
Black's active minor pieces and win the battle for the open central files.
With a bishop on c8, Black cannot coordinate his major pieces. Therefore, he
will lose the battle for the d-file. Besides the pressure in the centre and on
the queenside, White often manages to create threats against the black king.} 
*

