{[%csl Rb6,Rc5,Rc6] [#] Black's most typical way to develop the light-squared
bishop is to opt for ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7. In this case, an exchange of
the light-squared bishops usually happens. Even though the arising endgames
seem equal, Black often faces practical problems. The main issue is that the
advance ...b7-b5 weakens important squares on the queenside - c5, c6 and b6.
White pieces try to invade one of these weak spots. In order to cover his
queenside weaknesses, Black is forced to put his pieces on passive positions.
In such a case, White obtains an advantage since the activity of the pieces is
what matters in symmetrical positions.  In the examples that follow, I will
show some typical ways of using the queenside weaknesses. Additionally, the
training material will feature some favourable and unfavourable exchanges.}  *

