{[%evp 0,47,5,18,32,-11,-1,-42,-25,-30,-11,0,5,-2,-15,-9,5,34,32,14,44,44,57,
61,52,64,72,59,123,61,74,51,72,78,121,142,158,155,146,134,202,222,221,229,214,
214,214,222,229,213] Queenside Pressure We start with a model game in which
White used the queenside pressure in it's purest form.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
g3 d5 4. d4 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 {In this line, Black provokes the
exchange of the queens, thus reaching a typical Catalan endgame. This
variation is considered to be solid but less ambitious.} 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1
Bxc5 9. Nbd2 O-O $6 {This is already an inaccuracy. If White manages to regain
the c4-pawn without accepting a positional concession, Black will find himself
in an annoying position without counterplay.} ({Black should have preferred} 
9... c3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 {when the weak c3-pawn compensates White
queenside pressure. The position is balanced.}) 10. Nxc4 Nd5 $6 {This is
already a mistake. In such structures, the knight is usually unstable on d5.} (
{Black should have given priority to the problematic c8-bishop by playing} 
10... Ng4 11. e3 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] followed by ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. Even
in this case, however, White would enjoy a slight edge due to the weaknesses
provoked by the advance ...b7-b5.}) 11. Nfe5 $1 {The most precise reaction.
Besides opening the way of the g2-bishop, White wants to exchange a pair of
knights. Just to remind, White is interested in exchanging Black's minor
pieces (with the exception of the c8-bishop).} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 f6 13. Nc4 Nb6 $2
{Black makes White's task a lot easier. Instead of thinking about the
queenside development, he keeps playing with a developed piece.} ({Better
would have been} 13... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] , planning ...b7-b6 followed by
...Bb7. In my opinion, White's best would be the theamtic} 14. Na5 $1 {Very
often, the a5-square is a perfect spot for the white knight. From this
position, the knight puts pressure on the queenside and is ready to invade the
c6-square in case of ...b7-b6. In the next examples, I will provide more
detailed coverage of the weak c6-square.  In this position, a possible
continuation would be} b6 15. Nc6 Rb7 16. b4 Bd7 17. bxc5 Bxc6 18. cxb6 Rxb6
19. Ba3 $14 {White's bishop pair and active pieces secure a lasting advantage.}
) 14. Na5 {Once again, we see the same typical pattern.} ({Another typical
idea would be} 14. Be3 $1 {In such endgames, the exchange of the dark-squared
bishops is clearly favourable for White. After this exchange, white rooks can
easily penetrate Black's position via the squares d6 and c7.} {The play might
continue} Bxe3 15. Nxe3 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] followed by a2-a4-a5 and Rd6
in many lines. Black cannot untie himself.}) 14... Rb8 15. Bd2 {[%cal Ga1c1]
White just brings all his pieces into the game. His next move will be Rac1.}
Nd5 16. Rac1 Bb6 17. Nc4 Bc7 $2 {A mistake in a difficult position.} ({More
tenacious would have been} 17... Bc5 {, keeping the e3-square under control.
Of course, after} 18. a3 Re8 19. b4 Be7 20. e4 Nb6 21. Nxb6 axb6 22. Be3 $16 {
White's advantage is undisputable.}) 18. Ne3 $1 {Exchanging Black's only
active piece. The queenside pressure is getting tremendous.} Nxe3 19. Bxe3 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc7] This position is a typical lesson of White can happen if Black
fails to develop his queenside. White is winning.} Be5 20. Bc5 Re8 21. f4 Bc7
22. Bxa7 Ra8 23. Rxc7 Rxa7 24. a3 1-0

