{[%evp 0,87,16,28,28,-16,-3,-16,-18,-33,-5,14,2,-8,43,-24,5,-3,-17,-16,4,-52,
-14,-28,-11,-35,-5,-14,-9,-22,44,43,38,61,81,6,54,25,23,28,62,55,61,109,102,94,
94,65,73,76,59,41,62,65,65,63,91,63,63,84,85,82,101,110,116,85,93,95,101,102,
104,103,107,122,131,106,160,140,202,178,200,216,228,236,220,216,319,328,349,
366] [#] In the next two examples, we shall take a look at an endgame which is
a dream for every Catalan player. Let's take a look at the position on the
diagram. Very often in the Catalan endgames, Black's knight is forced into the
passive b8-square in order to cover the weakness of c6. At the same time, the
white rook is well placed on the weak c5-square.  In this position, Nyback
went for the thematic} 27. Rc7+ $1 {When your opponent has weaknesses,
exchanging a pair of rooks is usually a good strategy. By doing so, we
restrict the opponent's counterplay.} Rxc7 28. Rxc7+ Rd7 29. Rc8 $1 {Of course,
in order to effectively attack the weaknesses of our opponent, it is advisable
to keep one pair of rooks. With his last move, White forces the rook of his
opponent into a passive position.} Rb7 30. Nd3 {[%cal Gd3c5] This is an
absolutely model position for every Catalan player. One pair of rooks has been
exchanged, Black's queenside is weakened, and White has a knight on d3. The
d3-square is the perfect spot for the white knight. Depending on the
circumstances, the knight can go either to c5 or b4 in order to make use of
the queenside weaknesses. Additionally, the knight closes the d-file, thus
making sure that Black is deprived of any counterplay. Generally speaking, in
this structure, the c-file is more important than the d-file. The explanation
is simple - the d-file is closer to the kings. Therefore, the control of the
c-file is more profitable.} Ke7 31. Nc5 {Making use of the weak c5-square is a
thematic idea in the Catalan endgames.} Rb6 32. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Gc5] The most
technical decision. Besides strengthening the position of the knight, White
also fixes the a6-pawn. Fixing the opponent's weaknesses is an important
strategy when converting an advantage.} Nd7 33. Rc7 Rd6 34. Ra7 {Black is
completely tied. After preventing any kind of counterplay, White will simply
collect the queenside pawns. The position is technically winning.} Rd2 35. a3
e5 36. Kf3 f5 37. Ke3 {As mentioned earlier, the king easily neutralizes the
invasion along the d-file.} Rd6 38. Nxa6 $18 Kf8 39. Nc7 Nb6 40. Nxb5 Nc4+ 41.
Kf3 Rd2 42. Rc7 e4+ 43. Kf4 Nb2 44. Nc3 1-0

