{[%evp 0,82,28,22,25,27,29,-14,-14,-34,-6,10,14,17,32,-15,-23,-16,-6,-12,-12,
-11,3,-32,-18,-11,3,-11,-7,-29,-29,-22,20,15,29,26,25,25,44,47,53,49,65,50,51,
46,55,45,45,45,73,73,78,47,93,41,111,92,91,91,99,94,113,127,128,115,119,128,
131,129,130,206,186,140,191,205,237,234,246,246,253,253,300,328,320] [#] The
next example is taken from the practice of the great Catalan expert and
endgame virtuoso GM Ulf Andersson. Once again, we see the typical
configuration - knight and rook versus knight and rook. This time, the
c6-squre is occupied by the knight. Actually, the knight is very well placed
here as well since it dominates the black rook. Of course, in the future, the
white rook shall invade via the c6-square. For example, White can achieve a
tremendous advantage by means of simple moves such as Rc1 followed by Ne5 and
Rc6.} 24. Rc1 Na4 $2 {The knight is poorly placed in the edge of the board.} ({
Preferable would have been} 24... Nd7 {Even in this case, however, White keeps
pressing. For example, a good idea would be to gain space on the kingside by
means of} 25. f4 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gc1d1,Gd1d6,Ge2e4,Ge4e5] Later on, White can
proceed with Kf3, Rd1-d6 followed by e2-e4-e5. Black has no counterplay.}) 25.
b3 Nb6 26. Kf3 {Such slow and overcautious moves are typical for the style of
Ulf Andersson. Since Black has no counterplay, bringing the king closer to the
centre makes a lot of sense.} g5 27. Ne5 Rd8 ({The knight endgame arising after
} 27... Rc8 28. Rxc8+ Nxc8 29. Nc6 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5][%cal Gf3e3,Ge3d4,Gd4c5] is
very difficult for Black due to the vulnerable queenside. The white king is
heading for the c5-square.}) 28. Rc6 Nd7 29. Nd3 $1 {White has reached his
dream position - the knight is on the perfect d3-square.} ({Andersson is not
tempted by the possible win of a pawn with} 29. Nxd7 Rxd7 30. Rxa6 Rd2 {
Even though White should be winning, rook endgames provide the weaker side
with good drawing chances.}) 29... Nb8 {As usual, the knight is stuck to the
b8-square.} 30. Rc7 Kg7 31. Ne5 Rf8 32. b4 $18 {Black is completely paralyzed.
The rest is simple.} Kf6 33. Ke4 Kg7 34. a3 Kf6 35. Rb7 Kg7 36. f4 gxf4 37.
gxf4 Kg8 38. Nxf7 Rxf7 39. Rxb8+ Kg7 40. Rb6 Ra7 41. Rxe6 a5 1-0

