{[%evp 0,107,16,11,15,-11,-14,-11,-3,-10,55,-11,60,-25,40,12,9,-25,-50,-52,5,
-52,-80,-72,-105,-72,-79,-77,-76,-76,-38,-47,5,5,10,10,22,24,19,24,21,21,29,33,
37,50,39,51,51,30,43,19,43,33,30,29,45,55,46,44,51,37,37,30,42,49,55,34,47,38,
67,74,74,75,91,70,85,74,92,101,69,71,151,152,170,188,191,209,228,217,240,247,
221,255,315,319,329,388,389,384,384,406,440,435,541,550,717,727,29999,-30000] 
[#] In this structure, the d3-knight can dominate even the black bishop.
Usually, when the play goes on both wings, the bishop is stronger. In this
case, however, Black's queenside problems prevent him from playing on this
wing.  Let's take a look at the position on the diagram. The black rook is
tied to the defence of the weak a6-pawn. This weakness, however, is not enough
for White to win the game. He should try to create new targets. Therefore,
Keith Arkell started gaining space on the kingside by means of} 29. f4 $1 {
[%csl Rd5,Re6][%cal Gg2f3,Gg3g4,Gf4f5,Gf3e4,Gd3f4] A thematic pawn advance in
this structure. White is planning to weaken the white squares by means of
g3-g4 and f4-f5. In this case, the king can reach the d5 square while the
e6-square would be a perfect spot for the knight. At the same time, Black has
no active play in this position. The next few moves are quite logical.} Kf8 30.
g4 Bd8 31. Kf3 a5 32. a3 a4 33. f5 {Finally, White is ready to go for this
thematic idea. Now, Black should reckon with Nf4.} exf5 34. gxf5 Be7 {[%cal
Gc6c4,Gc4h4] Black's counterplay is based on the maeuver ...Rc4-h4.} ({Another
logical attempt would have been to take the f4-square under control by means of
} 34... Bc7 35. h3 g6 36. Rb7 Rc4 37. Rxb5 Rh4 {Even though White's chances
are preferable, Black has a reasonable counterplay.}) 35. Rb7 Rc4 36. Rxb5 Rh4
37. Rb8+ {Arkell starts playing against the black king. It turns out, however,
that Black has enough defensive resources.} ({More precise would have been} 37.
Nf4 $1 Rxh2 38. Ra5 $16 {[%cal Gf4e6,Ga5a4] when White's advantage is close to
winning.}) 37... Kf7 38. Rb7 Kf8 $6 {This is not a good square for the king
since the knight would land on e6 with a tempo.} ({More tenacious would be} 
38... Ke8) 39. Nf4 Rxh2 40. Ra7 Rh1 $2 {This is the decisive mistake.} ({
Black should have gone for} 40... Rf2+ 41. Kg3 Rf1 42. Ne6+ Kf7 43. Nd4 {
[%cal Gd4c6]} Rc1 44. Rxa4 g5 {with at least some counterplay.}) 41. Rxa4 $18 {
White has a winning advantage.} Rb1 42. Ra8+ Kf7 43. Ra7 Kf8 44. b4 Ra1 45.
Ne6+ Kf7 46. Nxg7 Rg1 47. Ne6 Ke8 48. Nc7+ Kf8 49. Nd5 Bd6 50. Nxf6 Rf1+ 51.
Ke4 Rf4+ 52. Kd5 Rxf5+ 53. Ke6 Rf2 54. Rf7# 1-0

