{[%evp 0,161,28,29,25,25,29,-14,0,-33,-14,-18,1,13,32,28,0,0,11,4,4,10,7,-5,-4,
-2,3,3,1,1,-3,-16,1,-61,-45,-45,-4,-15,-15,-15,-22,-5,1,1,-4,18,18,21,31,14,29,
9,40,-6,21,-21,13,6,12,16,77,71,71,69,70,71,78,67,62,55,48,48,48,60,66,43,48,
51,76,67,67,79,76,93,104,100,95,97,133,145,140,138,136,101,145,143,145,158,144,
135,133,146,138,119,166,126,171,161,169,148,162,165,187,187,184,218,187,218,
184,184,184,184,184,44,82,82,82,78,112,159,227,246,254,141,236,244,221,224,217,
287,266,274,274,236,346,333,350,198,168,140,223,175,177,159,159,100,71,8,547,
557,879,1015,1016,1016] [#] Now, we will examine a situation where Black has
pawns on a5 and b4. In general, this structure is even more favourable for
White. There are two factors that make Black's position difficult: 1) the
c4-square is available for White's pieces, mainly the knight 2) the a5-pawn
would be a serious weakness in every endgame.  At this point, Black went for} 
29... Rc8 $6 {This move allows White to force the transition into a favourable
endgame.} ({It seems that after} 29... Qb6 30. Qxb6 Nxb6 31. Rc1 Rc8 32. Rxc8+
Nxc8 {Black can hold the knight endgame. Since a similar position might arise
in your games, it makes sense to take a closer look at the typical methods of
playing in such endgames. My line is not forced but quite illustrative.  The
next few moves are quite logical:} 33. f3 Nb6 34. b3 Nd7 35. Kf2 Kf8 36. Ke3
Ke7 37. Kd4 Kd6 38. Nb2 {[%cal Gb2c4] A typical idea. Now, the drawback of
having a pawn on b4 becomes clear.} e5+ 39. Kd3 Nc5+ 40. Kc2 Ke6 41. Nc4 Nb7
42. e4 {The black knight is forced into a passive position. Now, White should
try to create a second weakness on the kingside. Therefore, Black starts
gaining space by means of} h5 43. Kd2 f6 44. Ke3 g5 $1 {This is the right
approach to the position. Since Black has gained a lot of space, White is no
longer able to obtain a kingside superiority.} ({The following line shows what
would happen if Black defends passively.} 44... Ke7 45. h4 Ke6 46. f4 g6 47.
Kf3 {This is a kind of a zugzwang. Black is forced to release the tension by
playing} exf4 48. Kxf4 Ke7 49. e5 Ke6 50. exf6 Kxf6 51. g4 hxg4 52. Kxg4 {
[%csl Ra5,Rg6] This position is winning for White. Besides his more active
pieces, he managed to create two weaknesses in Black's camp - a5 and g6.} Ke7
53. Kf3 Kf6 54. Ke3 Kf5 55. Kd4 $18 {The king is heading to the queenside.
White is winning.}) 45. f4 (45. h4 gxh4 46. gxh4 f5 $1 $11) 45... g4 $11 {
White cannot make progress.}) 30. Qxa5 Ra8 31. Qb5 Qxb5 32. axb5 Rb8 33. Rc1
Rxb5 {Once again, we have reached our favourite endgame - knight and rook
against knight and rook. The white knight occupies the perfect d3-square! Even
though Black exchanged a pair of pawns on the queenside, the b4-pawn requires
defence. Therefore, Black's pieces will be forced into passive positions. In
such positions, Black is usually trying to save the game in a rook endgame
with a pawn down.} 34. Rc8+ Kh7 35. e4 Nf6 36. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3] The
construction f3-e4 is very effective against a knight on f6.} g5 {[%cal Gg5g4]
A typical move in this structure. The threat is ...g5-g4. Therefore, White
should go for} 37. g4 Rb7 38. Kf2 h5 39. h3 hxg4 40. hxg4 b3 ({The alternative
} 40... Nd7 {is not better. For instance, after} 41. Ke3 Kg7 42. Kd4 b3 43. Rc4
Kf6 44. e5+ Ke7 45. Rb4 Rb8 46. Rxb8 Nxb8 47. Nb4 $16 {the knight endgame is
very difficult for Black.}) 41. Nc5 Ra7 42. Ke3 Kg7 43. Rb8 Rc7 44. Nd3 Nd7 45.
Rxb3 $18 {White's position is technically winning.} Kf6 46. Rc3 Rb7 47. Kd4 Ra7
48. Ra3 Rc7 49. Rc3 Ra7 50. Ra3 Rc7 51. b4 Rc2 52. Ra7 Nb6 53. Ra6 Nd7 54. Ra7
Nb6 55. Ra6 Nd7 56. b5 Rd2 57. Kc3 Rd1 58. Ra7 Nb6 59. Ra6 Nd7 60. Ra7 Nb6 61.
Rb7 Na4+ 62. Kb4 Rxd3 63. Kxa4 Rxf3 64. Rc7 Rf1 65. b6 Ke5 66. Rc4 Rb1 67. Rb4
Ra1+ 68. Kb5 Ra8 69. b7 Rb8 70. Kc6 Kf4 71. Kc7 Rg8 72. Rd4 (72. b8=Q Rxb8 73.
Rxb8 Kxe4 74. Kd6 Kf3 75. Rf8 $18) 72... f6 73. b8=Q $4 (73. Rd8 $1 Rg7+ 74.
Rd7 Rg8 75. Rf7 Kxe4 76. Rxf6 $18) 73... Rxb8 74. Kxb8 Kxg4 75. Kc7 e5 76. Ra4
Kf4 77. Kd6 g4 78. Kd5 g3 $4 (78... f5 $1 79. exf5+ Kxf5 80. Ra8 Kf4 81. Rf8+
Ke3 $11) 79. Ra8 f5 80. Rf8 g2 81. Rxf5+ 1-0

