{[%evp 0,91,16,25,29,-11,-9,-29,-29,-59,5,-1,3,-18,17,-31,0,-49,-20,-15,-1,-11,
10,-57,5,-16,50,9,17,15,14,-7,2,9,36,16,-1,1,18,-5,27,36,20,-15,-6,0,15,1,12,4,
17,15,45,37,65,53,47,37,42,44,44,42,41,52,47,45,70,54,70,101,93,91,110,95,99,
96,85,103,106,116,138,123,240,258,280,265,275,248,425,426,488,480,569,593] [#]
So far we have been mainly looking at positions where Black was forced to
cover his queenside weaknesses provoked by the move ...b7-b5.  Now, we shall
take a look at an example with a pawn on b7. As we are going to witness, even
in this case, Black faces some slight practical problems. White's main
strategy is to gain space on the kingside and force Black's minor pieces into
passive positions. With a precise play, however, Black can achieve a full
equality.} 24. f4 $1 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gg3g4,Gh2h4,Gg4g5] We are already familiar
with this thematic move which wins space on the kingside. White can proceed
with Kf3 followed by g2-g4, h2-h4, and g4-g5. Another idea is to gain space in
the centre by means of e2-e4.} Kf8 $6 {This is an inaccuracy.} ({Black should
have tried to gain space on the kingside as well. There are two ideas in that
direction.} 24... Nd5 25. Kf3 f5 $1 $11 {Gaining space by means of ...f7-f5
secures the stability of Black's minor pieces.}) ({and} 24... Ne4 $5 25. Be3 f5
$132 {[%cal Ye7f6,Yg8f7] followed by ...Bf6 and ...Kf7. Black has nothing to
worry about.}) 25. Kf3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gg3g4,Gh2h4,Gg4g5] White is already
better since Black cannot execute the thematic ...f7-f5.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]}
26. Be3 $1 {An important prophylactic move designed to prevent ...Nc5.} Ke8 27.
Bd4 {The play of Giri is really instructive. It turns out that Black cannot
protect the g7-pawn without accepting some sort of concession.} Bf6 {The
exchange of the dark-squared bishops favours White. When the knights are the
only minor pieces on the board, space is what matters.} ({Better would have
been} 27... g5 28. e4 f6 $14 {with a passive but solid position.}) 28. Bxf6
Nxf6 29. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] The e5-knight puts an annoying pressure on Black's
position.} Ke7 30. e4 Rxc1 31. Rxc1 Ne8 32. Nd3 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf3e4,Gg3g4,Gf4f5,
Ga4a5,Gd3c5,Gc1c3,Gc3b3] Again, the knight occupies the d3-square. White can
now consider expanding in the centre and on the queenside by means of e4-e5
followed by Ke4. Later, even g3-g4 followed by f4-f5 can be an option. Another
idea is to fix the b7-pawn by means of a4-a5. Afterwards, White can put
pressure on b7 by playing Nc5 followed by Rc3-b3.} a5 {Preventing a4-a5 but
weakening the b5-square.} ({In response to} 32... g5 {White can play} 33. fxg5
$5 hxg5 34. h4 $14 {creating a potentially dangerous distant passed pawn.}) 33.
Rc5 Kd6 $6 ({More tenacious would have been} 33... Rd8 $1 34. Ke3 b6 35. Rc6
Rd6 36. Rc4 f6 $14 {when White still needs to prove his advantage.}) 34. Rc3 $1
{[%cal Yd3c5,Yc3b3] White is planning to attack the queenside by means of Rb3
and Nc5.} ({The natural} 34. Rb5 $6 {would have allowed} Kc7 $14 {[%cal Gb7b6,
Ge8d6] when Black achieves stability. His next moves would be ...Nd6 and ...
b7-b6.}) 34... Ra6 $6 (34... Ke7 35. Rb3 Ra7 36. e5 $16) (34... b6 35. Ne5 $16)
35. e5+ Ke7 (35... Kd5 $2 36. Rc8 $18 {[%csl Re8]}) 36. Nc5 Rb6 37. Rd3 $1 {
[%csl Re8] It turns out that Black cannot prevent the invasion. One can easily
spot the tremendous difference in the piece activity.} Rxb2 38. Rd7+ Kf8 39.
Nxb7 {[%cal Rb7d8,Rb7a5]} Rb3+ (39... Rc2 40. Nxa5 Nc7 41. Rd8+ Ke7 42. Rd6 $16
{/+-}) 40. Kg4 Rb4 41. Nd8 $18 {White is already winning.} Kg8 42. Re7 $1 f5+ (
42... Kf8 43. Rxf7+ Kg8 44. Re7 Kf8 45. Ra7 $18) 43. Kh5 Kh7 44. Rxe8 Rb2 45.
h3 $8 Rh2 46. Kh4 $8 {[%csl Re6]} 1-0

