{[%evp 0,141,24,25,30,-7,-7,-34,-30,-30,-19,-10,9,13,40,-13,-11,-18,-17,-18,3,
-27,13,-19,11,0,36,16,10,10,3,19,13,19,-1,-38,3,-53,-41,-15,-12,-3,16,-5,-5,29,
57,22,30,43,60,65,51,68,69,71,73,73,67,72,75,57,59,69,72,65,77,58,77,64,67,42,
55,67,72,55,80,92,102,82,75,76,124,124,127,126,126,121,120,120,120,120,122,135,
134,134,142,143,125,187,187,139,200,205,204,207,222,233,241,251,256,247,266,
282,283,266,261,272,302,318,342,355,355,355,359,304,296,350,370,368,364,370,
410,414,489,539,538,541,655,677,1289,1289,1631,1801] Now, we shall take a look
at two examples in which Black failed to carry out the advance ...c7-c5. Such
endgames can be highly unpleasant for Black since he has no counterplay. On
the other hand, White's strategy is fairly simple. After taking control of the
d-file and blocking the c7-pawn, he will start expanding in the centre. In
this position, Caruana played} 27. Rd1 {One should always prioritize the
control of the only open file.} Nb6 28. Na5 $1 {Good prophylactic move. White
prevents Black from playing ...Nc4.} g6 29. e3 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gc2c6] The
idea of this little move is the untie the c2-rook from the defence of the pawn.
The rook will be perfectly placed on c6.} Kg7 30. Rd3 Rac8 31. Rc6 {[%csl Rc7]
[%cal Gd3d6] White's play is very instructive. All his pieces are optimally
placed. Now, he should gradually prepare his central expansion.} Rb8 32. Kf1 h5
33. h3 Kf6 34. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gf1e2,Gf2f4,Ge2f3,Ge3e4] Caruana is
perfectly coordinating his pieces. The knight is going to b3. At the same time,
White prepares the advance of his central pawns. His idea is simple - Ke2(g2),
f2-f4 followed by Kf3 and e3-e4.} Kg7 35. Ndb3 Re6 36. Kg2 Kf8 37. f4 Ree8 38.
Kf3 Red8 39. Rc2 Rd7 40. e4 Ke8 41. e5 {White managed to execute his main plan
without facing any difficulties.} Be7 42. Rxd7 Kxd7 43. Rd2+ Ke8 44. Nc6 {
By installing a knight on c6, White prevents Black from fighting for the
d-file.} Ra8 45. Nba5 {[%csl Gc4] Of course, the c4-square should be covered.}
f5 $6 {This makes things easier for White.} ({More tenacious would have been} 
45... f6 {Even in this case, however, Black's position remains horrible.}) 46.
g4 $1 {White opens a second battlefield. Black will not be able to hold the
position.} hxg4+ 47. hxg4 fxg4+ 48. Kxg4 Kf7 49. Rh2 Bf8 50. f5 {The most
natural move.} Nd5 51. f6 Nxf6+ $2 {Of course, this move leads to a lost
position. Nevertheless, the alternatives would not help either.} 52. exf6 $18 {
White is winning. The remaining part of the game needs no comments.} Kxf6 53.
Rf2+ Ke6 54. Re2+ Kd5 55. Rd2+ Ke4 56. Nb7 Ke3 57. Rd7 Re8 58. Rxc7 Bh6 59. Nc5
Rf8 60. Re7+ Kd2 61. Re6 Rf1 62. Na7 Be3 63. Rxa6 Ke2 64. Rxg6 Rf4+ 65. Kh3
Rf3+ 66. Rg3 Rf7 67. Nxb5 Bf2 68. Rb3 Rf4 69. Nc3+ Kf1 70. Rb1+ Be1 71. Rxe1+
1-0

