-22,-4,8,26,23,38,48,42,54,60,65,65,35,61,74,64,56,104,79,143,119,136,207,213,
213,280,280,273,279,294,294,296,303,355,347,349,316,391,431,427,431] [#]
Another clear example of how to play in this structure was featured in the
game Hammer - Ivanchuk.  In this position, Hammer played the natural} 29. Nc6 {
First of all, White blocks the c-pawn, thus making sure that Black cannot play
...c7-c5.} Re6 30. Rc2 $1 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d8] Another subtle positional move.
As mentioned earlier, the control of the d-file is an important part of
White's strategy. Therefore, he prepares Rd1.} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 31. b3 Kf8
32. Rd1 Ke8 33. Nd4 {Since Black can no longer opt for ...c7-c5, White can use
his knight in order to prepare the central expansion. The idea is to meet} Rf6
{with} 34. e4 {Black's position is completely hopeless. The advance e4-e5 is
coming.} Rg6 35. e5 Be7 36. Rxc7 Nd5 37. Rb7 Bd8 38. Nf5 Nf4+ 39. Kf3 Bxa5 40.
gxf4 Bb4 41. Rdd7 Rc8 42. Rxf7 Rc3+ 43. Ke4 1-0

