{[%evp 0,131,25,30,28,28,30,-23,31,16,15,-14,14,2,8,8,10,11,11,21,-6,1,-7,-7,
21,0,15,-7,-7,-15,-2,17,18,9,16,40,61,52,44,49,51,56,90,84,71,75,99,92,91,88,
90,82,98,93,92,93,101,92,101,93,97,91,100,91,95,81,96,96,101,73,91,102,98,104,
97,98,97,97,102,99,109,109,102,102,124,121,113,108,120,112,115,115,115,115,115,
115,115,113,133,131,137,139,139,138,139,137,129,133,125,132,131,132,145,150,
162,125,206,92,152,172,160,98,106,534,688,766,824,916,992,1002,1022,1022,1016,
1022] At the end of the current lecture, I would like to discuss an endgame
which arises from one of the currently fashionable variations. The central
position is being reached after} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. c4
O-O 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 c5
12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. f3 {Even though the position seems
equal, White has some long-term advantages. The presence of opposite coloured
bishops favours White since the black bishop is restricted. If the queens
remain on the board, White can try to build a kingside attack by advancing the
g- and h-pawns. On the other hand, if Black exchanges the queens, White will
enjoy an advantage in the endgame due to Black's structural weaknesses. This
is what happened in the current game.} Nd5 16. Bd4 Rfd8 17. e4 Nxc3 18. Bxc3
Qc5 19. Qa5 $1 {White tries to force the transition into an endgame with
opposite-coloured bishops which turns out to be very difficult for Black.} Qxa5
{Black goes for the endgame.} ({In my opinion, he should have kept the queens
on the board. A possible line would be} 19... Qe3+ 20. Kb1 Rd3 ({An improved
version of the endgame can be reached after} 20... Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 f6 22. Rd8+
Rxd8 23. Qxd8+ Kf7 24. Qd7+ Kg6 25. a3 Qd3+ 26. Qxd3 cxd3 27. Kc1 f5 $11 {
when Black's counterplay comes just in time.}) 21. Qe5 f6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23.
Rde1 Qc5 {with compensation for the pawn.}) 20. Bxa5 Rd3 21. Rxd3 cxd3 22. Kd2
Ba6 23. Rc1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5,Gc1c7] Forcing the exchange of the rooks.}
Rc8 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25. Kxd3 {The type of endgame we have on the board is very
important for everyone who plays this line. Even though Black's defensive
resources shouldn't be underestimated, I failed to find a clear path to the
draw. Besides being a pawn up, White has a very active king. The next moves
are not forced but logical.} Ba6+ 26. Kd4 Be2 27. f4 Kf8 28. Kc5 Bd3 29. e5 Ke8
30. Kc6 a6 31. Kc7 h5 32. Kc8 Bb1 33. a3 Bd3 34. b4 {It turns out that White
will create a passed pawn on the b-file.} Bb5 35. Bb6 Ke7 36. Bc5+ Ke8 37. Be3
Ke7 38. Kc7 Ke8 39. Bc5 g6 40. Be3 Ke7 41. Bd4 Ke8 42. Bc5 Ba4 43. Kb7 Bb5 44.
a4 Bxa4 45. Kxa6 Kd7 46. b5 {This is the position White was going for. In my
opinion, this position is lost for Black. The f7-pawn is Black's second
weakness (the first one is White's b5-pawn). White's long-term plan is to
create a passed pawn on the kingside after winning the f7-pawn. In such
endgames, we usually win when we have two passed pawns which cannot be
controlled (by the opponent's bishop) via one single diagonal.} Kc8 47. Kb6 Kd7
48. Bb4 Kc8 ({The bishop cannot leave the a4-square. For example, after} 48...
Bd1 {White is winning -} 49. Kb7 Bf3+ 50. Kb8 Bg2 51. b6 Kc6 52. Ka7 $18) 49.
Kc6 Kd8 50. Bc3 Kc8 51. Ba5 Kb8 52. Kc5 Kb7 53. b6 Bc2 {Black applies the
classical defensive strategy - the king block's the opponent's passed pawn
while the bishop protects the remaining pawns. Black's problem is that after
taking on f7, White will manage to create a second passed pawn.} 54. Kd6 Be4
55. Ke7 Ka6 56. Kxf7 Kxa5 $2 {This move loses immediately.} ({More stubborn was
} 56... Bf5 {In this case, White should apply the following plan: 1) bring the
king to c5 in order to protect the pawn 2) transfer the bishop to f2 3)
transfer the king to h4 4) created a second passed pawn by means of h2-h3,
g3-g4 and f4-f5, in the suitable moment. Below, I provide some sample lines.}
57. Ke7 Kb7 58. Kd6 Bg4 59. Kc5 {The first part of the plan is completed.} Bf5
60. Be1 Bg4 61. Bf2 {The second part is over. Now, the bishop safely protects
the b6-pawn.} Bf5 62. Kd6 Bg4 63. Ke7 Bf5 64. Kf6 Kc6 65. Kg5 Kb7 66. Kh4 {
White managed to complete the third step. He is now ready to prepare the
creation of a passed pawn.} Be4 ({The alternative} 66... Kc6 {does not help
either. For instance, after} 67. h3 Be4 68. Kg5 Kb7 69. g4 hxg4 70. hxg4 Kc6 (
70... Bf3 71. f5 gxf5 72. gxf5 exf5 73. e6 Kc8 74. Kxf5 $18) 71. Kf6 Kd7 72. b7
Bxb7 73. Kxg6 Ke8 74. Bc5 $18 {[%cal Gg6f6,Gg4g5,Gg5g6]}) 67. h3 Bg2 68. g4
hxg4 69. hxg4 Kc8 70. Kg5 Bh3 71. Kh4 Bg2 72. f5 exf5 (72... gxf5 73. g5 $18)
73. e6 {Finally, White managed to create a second passed pawn and the game is
over.} Bd5 74. e7 Kd7 75. Bc5 f4 76. Kg5 f3 77. Kf6 Ke8 78. Ke5 Bb7 79. Kd6 $18
) 57. Kxe6 Kxb6 58. Kd6 Bd3 59. e6 Bb5 60. h3 Kb7 61. g4 hxg4 62. hxg4 Kc8 63.
Ke7 Bd3 64. Kf8 Bb5 65. e7 Kc7 66. e8=Q 1-0

